CREATE TABLE MonthlyData AS
SELECT 
	strftime('%Y-%m', ordersAdj.new_order_date) Month, -- using reformatted date from ordersAdj
	ROUND(SUM(order_items.sales), 2) AS MonthlySales,
    ROUND(SUM(order_items.sales * (products.category = 'Technology')), 2) AS TechSales,
    ROUND(SUM(order_items.sales * (products.category = 'Office Supplies')), 2) AS SuppliesSales,
    ROUND(SUM(order_items.sales * (products.category = 'Furniture')), 2) AS FurnitureSales,
    
    ROUND(SUM(order_items.profit), 2) AS MonthlyProfits,
    ROUND(SUM(order_items.profit * (products.category = 'Technology')), 2) AS TechProfits, -- changes were made via Gemini to increase volume of workflow
    ROUND(SUM(order_items.profit * (products.category = 'Office Supplies')), 2) AS SuppliesProfits,
    ROUND(SUM(order_items.profit * (products.category = 'Furniture')), 2) AS FurnitureProfits,

	ROUND(100.0*SUM(order_items.discount * order_items.quantity) / SUM(order_items.quantity), 2) AS AverageDiscount, -- percentage discount reads stronger than a decimal discount
	SUM(order_items.quantity) MonthlySalesQuantity,
	SUM(CASE WHEN products.category = 'Furniture' THEN order_items.quantity ELSE 0 END) FurnitureQuantity,
  SUM(CASE WHEN products.category = 'Office Supplies' THEN order_items.quantity ELSE 0 END) SuppliesQuantity,
  SUM(CASE WHEN products.category = 'Technology' THEN order_items.quantity ELSE 0 END) TechQuantity
FROM order_items 
	JOIN ordersAdj ON ordersAdj.order_id = order_items.order_id -- order_id is common key
	JOIN products ON products.product_id = order_items.product_id -- product_id is common key
GROUP BY Month -- summing for monthly data


ANALYSIS: 

We see that the months are not equal.
MonthlySales range between 12036.17 and 120876.69, excluding the outlier in 2014-02 at just 4632.68 in sales. 
Ordering by MonthlySales, we find that the lowest 7 months for sales were all January or February, with 2017-01 as an outlier.
Similarly, we see that every instance of September, November or December were in the top 13 MonthlySales, with 2017-10 as an exception.
As a result, it is not fair to compare all months on their own. Further analysis must investigate in a single month or in a comparable group of months. 

While MonthlyProfits is still slightly skewed towards the later months, the correlation is a lot less blatant. 
There are two negative months in 2015-01 (-3211.81) and 2014-07 (-751.33), with all other MonthlyProfits between +901.92 and +18689.43
This signals that further analysis should involve the inspection of MonthlyProfits and any causality which results in marginal or negative months. 

